      },
      "lineNbr": 107,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2015-08-19T18:39:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "IMPORTANT: never use strcasecmp(), the result is locale-dependent and will surprise you greatly when running on a non-US locale, resulting in unexpected and hard-to-reproduce bugs.\n\nUse a custom ASCII-only implementation of strcasecmp() (if you need it, I suggest adding it to a new header like android/base/misc/CaseCompare.h with appropriate unit tests).\n\nAlso use a small function that will do the comparison and casting in one go, to make all use cases more legible.",
      "revId": "1fdb30c2599437d5b1d468c75f57ae5a1adcc5f5",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4486d92e_0c8fd739",
        "filename": "android/skin/qt/parse-location.h",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2015-08-19T18:39:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "nit: our convention for our sources files is to use a header guard macro that reflects the location of the source file, i.e. in this case, it should be ANDROID_SKIN_QT_PARSE_LOCATION_H\n\nHowever, since there is nothing specific to Qt here, and the same code could be easily reused elsewhere, I strongly propose to move it to a non-Qt specific location (e.g. android/gps/).\n\nFinally, for C++ files, it\u0027s better to use the name of the main class for the header/sources, using CapitalCamelCasing, i.e. in this example, this would be android/gps/KmlParser.h",
      "revId": "1fdb30c2599437d5b1d468c75f57ae5a1adcc5f5",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
